Nereus is made to speak be- cause the sea-gods were endowed 'with the gift of prophecy. Porphyrion on this ode says it is an imitation of Bacchylides, who makes Cassandra foretel the destruction of Troy as Horace does Nereus. There is a fragment (29 Bergk) which is supposed to belong to the poem referred ,to by this Scholiast, but it bears no resemblance to Horace's ode.

ARGUMENT'.

Paris is carrying off Helen, when Nereus causes a calm and thus prophesies their fate. With dark omen art thou carrying home her whom Greeoe hath swom to recover- Alas! for the sweating of horse and rider, and the deaths thou art bringing upon Troy. Pallas prepareth her arms and her fury. Under Venus' shelter oomb thy looks and strike thy lyre, and hide thyself in thy chamber z but it shall not avail thee. ,Seest thou not Laertes' son, Nestor of Pylos, Teucer of Salamis, aud Sthenelus the fighter and bold charioteer? Merion too and the son of Tydeus, from whom thou shalt fiee panting as the stag fleeth from the wolf, thou who didst boast better things to thy ffir- one.

Achilles’ wrath may put off the evil day, but the fire of the Greek shall consume the homes of Troy.
